feed.title: Brisbane Ranges surrounds - Plants
feed.subtitle:
This collection has been developed to cover the plants within the landscape of the Brisbane Ranges that surround the Brisbane Ranges National Park and Steiglitz Historic Park, but do not include observations within these reserves. Plant names will be added progressively as observations are made. Much of the surrounding land of the national park is native vegetation owned by private landholders or part of local government road reserves. Be sure to visit the collection called "Brisbane Ranges significant flora" to add any of your observations that are relevant to that collection.
For more info or questions, please email: brisbanerangesproject@gmail.com

entry.title: Moenchia erecta
entry.content: Weed along roadside.

entry.title: Cyanicula caerulea
entry.content: So much water on the petals it makes them look unusual.

entry.title: Pterostylis smaragdyna
entry.content: Many tens of plants both flowering and sterile. Higher density than observed in past.

entry.title: Crassula muscosa var. muscosa
entry.content: An well-established patch of succulent weed, which has originated from the entrance of a property on the east side of Bacchus Marsh-Balliang Road, and now spread across to the opposite side of the road and into private property. Infestation appears to be contained within a single patch, but has spread to approximately 30m along the roadside.

entry.title: Ozothamnus obcordatus
entry.content: Small flowering individual growing through Lomandra.

entry.title: Sporobolus africanus
entry.content: A patch along roadside, approximately 10x2m

entry.title: Plantago coronopus subsp. coronopus
entry.content: Growing on road pavement verge.

entry.title: Eriochilus cucullatus s.s.
entry.content: With a loose patch of about 8 other plants (flowering and in bud), growing at the immediate edge of the bitumen road through the spill of the basalt stones and bitumen.

entry.title: Olearia pannosa subsp. cardiophylla
entry.content: A young plant - evidence of recruitment at this population.

entry.title: Olearia pannosa subsp. cardiophylla
entry.content: Severely browsed by wallabies. One of only two plants of this species found in the near vicinity. The plant was caged to protect from Wallaby browsing. The other plant is also caged and approximately 30 metres away.

entry.title: Olearia pannosa subsp. cardiophylla
entry.content: One of only two plants of this species found in the near vicinity. The plant was caged to protect from Wallaby browsing. The other plant is also caged and approximately 30 metres away.

entry.title: Pomaderris prunifolia var. prunifolia
entry.content: Isolated mature plant. Only one other observed nearby.

entry.title: Glossodia major
entry.content: Double-flowered plant.

entry.title: Acacia aspera subsp. parviceps
entry.content: Area had been cleared - plants developing into substantial shrubs and flowering very well.

entry.title: Pultenaea graveolens
entry.content: Dense patch of young plants up to 1m tall.

entry.title: Tetratheca ciliata
entry.content: Unusual and rare pure-white flowering form of this species. Only a single plant observed among many typical flowered plants.

entry.title: Glossodia major
entry.content: Patch of numerous Glossodia major in flower along track beside road.

entry.title: Bossiaea obcordata
entry.content: First flower I have seen this season - plants are carrying lots of buds.

entry.title: Olearia minor
entry.content: This plant had a caterpillar which was feeding on the flower.

entry.title: Boronia anemonifolia subsp. anemonifolia
entry.content: The four or five plants found were very small having been eaten by herbivores (rabbits, wallabies or both) extensively.
